<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-311-518  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 311 518.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  April 3 1990 v4 n13 p67(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apple complaint prompts police raid on clone builders. (AkkordTechnology Inc., Flive Computer Corp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Said, Carolyn.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Apple is suing two Taiwanese companies for copyright and trademark infringement.andP;  Apple's legal action prompted Taiwaneseofficials to raid the headquarters of Akkord Technology Inc andFlive Computer Corp. Apple is suing five officials from thecompanies over the Jonathan microcomputer, which appears to be aMacintosh clone.andP;  After some initial difficulty, Apple purchasedseveral Jonathans, took them apart, and discovered that some ofthem contained illegally copied Mac ROMs and other Apple software.andO;After warning letters were ignored, Apple filed the suit.andP;  Akkordofficials say that the Jonathan is not available for sale, andthat the ROMs were taken out of an Apple product and placed in theJonathan for purposes of demonstration.andP;  The company is stillseeking to create a legal Mac clone.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (cases)Akkord Technology Inc. (investigations)Flive Computer Corp. (investigations).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Product:   Akkord Technology Jonathan (Microcomputer) (legal aspects).andO;Topic:     CompetitionCopyrightLegal Issues.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Carolyn SaidandM;Cupertino, Calif.andP;  -- Jonathan, the Macintosh clone demonstrated by aTaiwanese company last year, has finally drawn legal fire from Apple.andM;Apple announced last week that it has filed a criminal complaint in Taiwanagainst five people for infringing on its copyright and trademark rights,prompting Taiwanese officials to raid offices of the individuals' companies,Akkord Technology Inc. and Flive Computer Corp.andM;In addition to selling the Jonathan, the individuals had placedadvertisements suggesting that they were authorized Apple dealers anddistributors, Apple said.andM;Akkord gained notoriety a year ago when it showed what appeared to be a Macclone, albeit one that needed Apple ROMs to operate (see MacWEEK, Jan.andP;  3,1989, and April 18, 1989).andM;Apple has been trying to purchase a Jonathan since that splashy debut,according to Irv Rappaport, Apple associate general counsel.andP;  Afterinvestigators finally succeeded in purchasing several units, Apple took themapart and discovered that some of them contained illegally copied MacintoshROMs as well as other Apple software, Rappaport said.andM;The company sent warning letters asking the individuals involved to ceaseinfringing on Apple's copyrights and trademarks, Rappaport said.andP;  When Applereceived no reply to the letters, it filed the criminal complaint.andM;The Jonathan &quot;is not being offered for sale,&quot; said Luc Kwanten, a Taiwanconsultant representing Akkord.andP;  &quot;It's strictly a demonstration machine.&quot;andO;Furthermore, &quot;it was very clearly stated that the ROM in the Akkord machinewas taken out of an original Macintosh and placed in there for purposes ofdemonstration.&quot;andM;Akkord does want to make a legal Mac clone, Kwanten said.andP;  The company isinvestigating &quot;how to establish legal BIOS (basic input-output system) so themachine can run.andP;  At the same time, they are not intending to copy orplagiarize anything.&quot;andM;The Taipei District Court is expected to decide this week whether to issueindictments.andP;  Kwanten said that Akkord's Lloyd Chen, one of the five peoplecharged, plans to countersue Apple for libel, defamation of character andtrademark infringement if the court indicts him.andM;In an interview published in his company's newsletter in February, Chen saidthat Akkord had discontinued production of the Jonathan, &quot;though we've had todispose of a lot of inventories in stock.andM;&quot;In the past we've cloned most of the Mac series, but finally we decided notto continue in that direction until we get a software license from Apple,&quot;Chen said.andM;Chen ran up against Apple's aggressive stance in protecting its turf severalyears ago, when Apple sued him for making an Apple II clone.andM;Kwanten said that he thinks &quot;Apple is using its resources to preventlegitimate research being conducted by engineers in other countries into aproduct that could possibly compete with Apple.&quot; n</TEXT></DOC>